text:
this is real.
stop romanticizing the people who hurt you.
stop romanticizing your toxic parents because they gave you tough love (a.k.a.: abused you but fed you, too, so you should be grateful.) how about no?
stop romanticizing your ex who abused you but you kind of get it because he was also abused as a kid and you were kind of acting like a bitch? no!
stop romanticizing your favorite actors and directors because they are otherwise brilliant and extremely talented men apart from the fact that they abuse women and children on the side. well, no!
stop romanticizing your pain - acknowledge it! only after we acknowledge the pain and abuse for what they are, we can hold those who inflicted them accountable for their actions. 
is there anything you learned about emotional and covert abuse you wish you knew when you were younger? if you could go back in time, what would be the one advice you would give to your 13 year-old self? 
i would tell myself: "it gets better." have a splendid day. üçÉ (photo by @blcksmth)

text:
how are dark skin patches or acanthosis nigricans related to pcos? 
women with pcos (or pcod) often experience skin overgrowths including patches of dark, brown, velvety skin. these skin patches are properly known as acanthosis nigricans and can occur anywhere on the body. pcos skin conditions, which are usually aesthetically displeasing and invariably troubling to women, are quite common with pcos. one of the influencing factors of pcos, which is insulin resistance, can be managed with a healthy diet, regular exercise, and appropriate nutritional supplements.

polycystic ovarian syndrome (pcos) is an endocrine disorder that stems from an imbalance in sex hormones. your female reproductive system is regulated by a very delicate balance of ‚Äúmale‚Äù and ‚Äúfemale‚Äù sex hormones, namely estrogen, progesterone, and testosterone. when the levels of these sex hormones become imbalanced, your female reproductive system cannot function according to its normal routine. in the case of polycystic ovarian syndrome (pcos), your body creates too many male sex hormones and the high levels of testosterone prevent the female reproductive system from adhering to its menstrual cycle due to which skin pigmentation and hormonal acne show up on various body parts of the body.
.
.

text:
the 7th step in my book is "repeat". happy new year! here's to more success for us all in 2019 as we do the work, repeat the process and steps to achieve success in all areas of our lives! excerpt:"the last step in the process is to repeat all the above 6 steps. this is as important as any one of the other steps. see, the minute we plateau is the minute we lose momentum. i‚Äôm not talking about getting to the top of a mountaintop that you‚Äôve been climbing and not appreciating the hard work it took to get there-take time to appreciate yourself and all the hard work, sweat, blood and tears you put in getting to the top of that mountaintop. enjoy the view you‚Äôve worked so hard to attain. enjoy the euphoria that comes with it-appreciate the progress, healing, success, joy and love that you‚Äôve attained by doing all you‚Äôve done. you were willing to go where others weren‚Äôt willing to go. you were willing to tap into parts of yourself that others can‚Äôt even imagine doing. you didn't get here without a load of pain and suffering and you learned a lot along the way. you plunged into the depths of your heart and soul, uncovered what was there, layer by layer, unafraid (or you did it, despite being afraid) of what you would find, knowing that in doing so you would find the nuggets of truth you needed to move to your next level life. so, yes, enjoy the mountaintop experience, the view, all of it. speak your prayers of gratitude for love, hope and healing. then, recalibrate, repeat, and get yourself to the next level!" - excerpt from my book: "the lotus: how i beat the patriarchy"üìïüíØ

because so often moms put themselves at the bottom of the priority list.

text:
our capacity to feel safe in the world, to feel deep emotional intimacy, is a direct consequence of our capacity to feel safe in our bodies and to feel a deep intimacy with our self, with our body.

if my body holds trauma (physical, emotional, spiritual) i will have parts in me that does not feel safe. and those parts will ‚Äúspeak‚Äù by telling me ‚Äúthis is not safe‚Äù even if there is nothing in that specific moment that is truly unsafe.
.
‚Äúthere are wounds that never show on the body that are deeper and more hurtful than anything that bleeds.‚Äù
‚Äî  laurell k. hamilton, mistral's kiss.

as i am in the process of writing a book on trauma, exploring the physiological, physical, emotional and spiritual aspects of it, i wanted to share with you some of my findings and views on trauma.

my personal experience of discovering my sexual trauma has been a beautiful doorway into allowing me to express from an embodied experience what trauma feels like and what is the way through it, into healing.

read about it here:
http://bit.ly/traumaintimacy
(or link in bio to my blog)
.
thank you for all your beautiful messages of support for the past 48 hours, it has been really helpful to feel it all and to open this conversation.

here‚Äôs to a new year. 2018 was wakeful, as an individual and as a citizen of the world. more than any other year, the view of my life and my world shifted. amid the frustrations playing out on the global stage, i felt empowered by the individual voices who spoke out, sharing their stories, being brave so that we could collectively see the power in that. i‚Äôm grateful for #metoo, for every woman who testified at the larry nassar hearing, for @patagonia redirecting their tax credit back into the fight against climate change, for @i_weigh and the countless women proclaiming their sovereignty in a body-shame state, for christine blasey ford, for @gilliana and @ilizas and any public figure who uses their status to spread awareness on animals rights and the environment and every damn artist out there who is sacrificing a paid-off credit card and lord knows what else to live a life in the name of service to this planet and the beautiful human race upon it. we can and will do better. i truly believe in your good. i believe in my own. and i thank you. see you at the coffee shopüñ§. #2019resolutions #thankunext

text:
why has sex become so political? why is this conversation taking place outside of the bedroom of two consenting adults? 
now for clarity's sake...i could give a damn about what others deem acceptable in the bedroom. it's not my f*cking business. unnerstan' me?

i. don't. care. *reread 100x*

but what i do care about is the overt agenda that i have personally witnessed in my kayd's kindergarten classroom on up to olivia's grade to take away their ability to choose who they are and who they choose to love when they are old enough to make those decisions. my children are so so much more than a sexual identity. my children are so so much more than a nice-bullied ally for movements that have notoriously ridden black and brown backs to further causes that never ever fairly represent them or afford them the same rights and benefits as those do not look like them (black) or suffer from the systemic hatred that has shaped and affected them for several generations. 
what i do care about is being hetero-shamed by my community and my children, in my own home, so that i fear the instant backlash of being accused of not "being a friend of______" 
i am not going to be made fearful of expressing the desire to maintain the right of imparting lessons and values to my children at home. i do not teach hate but i do teach the love and knowledge and respect of self first and foremost. i do teach the need to protect and preserve the black family because it is and always has been under attack.

the jews have their allies. (dear god help us all not to appear antisemitic!!) the lbgt movement has many many friends in all the high places. white women and their #metoo bullshit are fine. dammit-peta has locked down the animals rights!! we are so much more than who we love and the sex acts we do in the privacy of our bedrooms. and i will continue to teach my children that until my very last breath. 
and that's my f*cking business.

2018, what a year for women. ‚Ä¢the #metoo movement continued to move into other countries, industries. as more survivors are speaking out about their abuse. still a lot are in silence, but at least their not suffering alone. christine blasey ford stood up against trump and his millions of fans for her country. in her ‚Äòcivic duty‚Äô she told the world her abuse suffered at the hands of one of her attackers supreme court judge now brett kavanaugh. she spoke out, but she‚Äôs still living in fear and hasn‚Äôt been able to return to her normal life, even after the attack, because of her courage and bravery she has inspired other survivors to speak out. she suffered the backlash, but also a lot of love. this atmosphere of love, unity against the vile abuse that was inflicted upon them is a great change. ‚Ä¢the women‚Äôs march against trump‚Äôs victory. over 3 million people marched in the usa. millions more around the world, even in london. some sources even say it was the largest peaceful protest in the whole of us history. activists supporting activists supporting change. this march was not simply in hatred for trump, it was the march for women‚Äôs fundamental rights, against gender inequality and patriarchy. all these women role models who have come out as feminists, despite the media‚Äôs attempt to show people its ‚Äòman-hating‚Äô. all these women creating a brighter future for us. changing the world‚Äôs policies, creating movements and inspiring change, on the right side of history. ‚Ä¢serena williams in her battle against sexism, showing girls all over the world, especially black girls it‚Äôs never okay to accept this kind of behaviour. ‚Ä¢in the republic of ireland they decriminalised abortion, giving women choice and freedom. which was a massive turning point in women‚Äôs rights, in terms of their money, health and support. ‚Ä¢the law against upskirting (taking a picture up someone‚Äôs skirt without consent was tried to turn into a sexual offence because it wasn‚Äôt even a crime against the body. ‚Ä¢the largest amount of women in us politics ever, and loads of diversity. we have stopped voting for politicians and instead become them, representation matters. üíõ
#believesurvivors #timesup #feminism

text:
the first year of the #metoo movement against workplace sexual harassment brought incredibly changes to the country and to the california capitol. this includes new protections at the office in 2019 and i am elated about them.
‚Ä¢
senate bill 820 forbids companies from forcing employees who settle sexual harassment complaints to sign non-disclosure agreements that prevent them from speaking out about what happened. a victim can choose to keep his or her name private, but the perpetrator‚Äôs name can no longer be confidential.
‚Ä¢
senate bill 1300 bans the business practice of requiring workers to sign releases of liability as a condition of continued employment or in exchange for a bonus.
‚Ä¢
senate bill 1343 calls for (nearly) every california employee to receive biannual sexual harassment training.
‚Ä¢
senate bill 826 compels public companies in california to have at least one female director on their boards by the end of the year.
‚Ä¢

coconut oil for hair

deep condition with a hair mask

hair conditioners often contain coconut oil because it easily penetrates the strands and can prevent protein and moisture loss.

tame edges

if you struggle with taming your edges, coconut oil can definitely help. rub a small bit of coconut oil between the pads of your fingers and run through particularly frizzy areas to leave hair looking smooth and polished. 
add shine and seal in moisture 
smooth a tiny amount of organic coconut oil onto the ends of your hair and also to the scalp to add a little shine and also to seal in moisture and keep your ends moisturized. 
minimize dandruff

coconut oil can help lower the levels of yeast on the skin that drive inflammation, flaking, and itching associated with dandruff. simply apply a thin layer of pure coconut oil to your clean scalp daily to combat dandruff. .
.

text: yesterday i had a really healing cranial sacral session with an incredible practitioner. üíõ i noticed there would be these waves of memories that would release. i imagine connected to the body releasing. üôè one that really surprised me was energy (trauma?) connected to what gets referred to as 9-11. a big tragedy that happened in the states. i was surprised to know that was held in my body all this time. üôè i‚Äôm quite focused on trauma healing currently because i‚Äôm realizing how widespread trauma is. perhaps we‚Äôve all been traumatized in various ways. spirit is calling me to focus specifically on trauma healing for our serbia retreat which is being planned for late july. üíõ thank you to my beautiful serbian sister @bijouxart for planting the seed. if you‚Äôve seen our film already you‚Äôve met her beautiful soul. she inspires me endlessly. she‚Äôs an extraordinary artist and has such a precious heart. üå∏ the message that i‚Äôm receiving is to call women/the feminine together to focus especially around healing our sexual trauma. remember #metoo us all it feels like. üíõ i trust we can do some really good healing together. we‚Äôll be in the sacred mountains of serbia. there‚Äôs also something that‚Äôs coming through about healing the oracles. we need to reclaim our voices as well as our right to use our voice for sharing what we know and what spirit shows us about the future. i‚Äôll be consulting with the kontomble to find out more specifics in the next few days. we‚Äôll be sharing this very soon. üå∏ it will also, absolutely be in honor and respect of the great goddess. i have become so inspired hearing bilyana‚Äôs stories about the heritage of serbia and the goddess culture. üôè. we are indeed remembering.... with love, liv mokai wheeler photo credit: jasmina68 #womenhealing #goddess #ritual #ceremony #serbia #shamanism #kontomble #feedingspiritfeedsus #traumahealing #reclaimyourvoice #guidedbyspirit

art tatum, the world renown king of jazz piano, walked into a bar that fat waller, the big pianist on the block at the time, was playing and waller stopped what he was doing, got up ans announced, "god is here!" on another occasion, art told bud powell that he'd play anything bud could with his right with his left hand. bud never recovered

art tatum is one of the greatest pianist to exist and his playing alone made pianist cower. to put into perspective, he was the mike tyson of piano. the micheal jordan. he remains so today and his influence is felt everywhere there's a piano. this is his rendition of george gershwin's "the man i love".

„Éª„Éª„Éª
this is real.
stop romanticizing the people who hurt you.
stop romanticizing your toxic parents because they gave you tough love (a.k.a.: abused you but fed you, too, so you should be grateful.) how about no?
stop romanticizing your ex who abused you but you kind of get it because he was also abused as a kid and you were kind of acting like a bitch? no!
stop romanticizing your favorite actors and directors because they are otherwise brilliant and extremely talented men apart from the fact that they abuse women and children on the side. well, no!
stop romanticizing your pain - acknowledge it! only after we acknowledge the pain and abuse for what they are, we can hold those who inflicted them accountable for their actions. 
is there anything you learned about emotional and covert abuse you wish you knew when you were younger? if you could go back in time, what would be the one advice you would give to your 13 year-old self? 
i would tell myself: "it gets better." have a splendid day. üçÉ (photo by @blcksmth)

text:
what can they do
to you? whatever they want.
they can set you up, they can
bust you, they can break
your fingers, they can
burn your brain with electricity,
blur you with drugs till you
can t walk, can‚Äôt remember, they can
take your child, wall up
your lover. they can do anything
you can‚Äôt blame them
from doing. how can you stop
them? alone, you can fight,
you can refuse, you can
take what revenge you can
but they roll over you.

but two people fighting
back to back can cut through
a mob, a snake-dancing file
can break a cordon, an army
can meet an army.
two people can keep each other
sane, can give support, conviction,
love, massage, hope, sex.
three people are a delegation,
a committee, a wedge. with four
you can play bridge and start
an organization. with six
you can rent a whole house,
eat pie for dinner with no
seconds, and hold a fund raising party.
a dozen make a demonstration.

a hundred fill a hall.
a thousand have solidarity and your own newsletter;
ten thousand, power and your own paper;
a hundred thousand, your own media;
ten million, your own country.

it goes on one at a time,
it starts when you care
to act, it starts when you do
it again after they said no,
it starts when you say we
and know who you mean, and each
day you mean one more.

the low road by marge piercy

text:
r kelly has repeatedly been charged with making child pornography. he's been accused of having sex with multiple underage girls. he's been accused of trapping women a sex cult, confiscating their phones and controlling every aspect of their lives. at the age of 27, he married aaliyah who was just 15 at the time and witnesses claim they were in a sexual relationship

and yet, despite all these accusations and the evidence against him, the women and girls speaking out against his actions are yet to see any justice

a man can get away with anything if he's powerful, rich or talented enough - especially if his victims are black women and girls

please #muterkelly, read up about the accusations made against him, and if you're able to access the surviving r kelly documentary, give it a watch

text:
girl powerüí™
.
study reveals that girls are more likely to envision themselves in leadership roles and gain more confidence when they see themselves reflected in superhero movies and television shows!
.
these findings from the women's media center and bbc america are yet another reminder that representation matters!
.
female sci-fi and superhero characters help bridge the confidence gap for girls, making them feel strong, brave, confident, inspired, positive, and motivated.‚Äù
.
. ‚Äúif you can‚Äôt see her, you can‚Äôt be her,‚Äù bbc america president sarah barnett implores. ‚Äúit‚Äôs time to expand what gets seen, and we hope this report will contribute to sparking change in the stories we see on screen. with greater representation of female heroes in the sci-fi and superhero genre, we can help superpower the next generation of women.‚Äù
.
.
.

text:
"new power is all around us and it's a new way to think about the exercise of power. we often use the comparison of harvey weinstein, the icon of old power, someone who used power ruthlessly as a currency in order to protect himself, to punish his enemies, to reward his friends, and therefore maintain this position despite all of this abuse and harassment. contrast that to the me too movement, which is an expression of new power. the me too movement is a kind of power that works less like a currency and more like a current. it's the kind of power that surges, it gets stronger the more people get involved‚Äî no one person can capture it or hoard it, but instead people learn to channel its energy."
„Éª„Éª„Éª
we kick off 2019 with a quick sit down with @jeremyheimans, co-founder & ceo of @purpose and author of new power: how power works in our hyperconnected world‚Äî and how to make it work for you. we get his take on new power and it's potential as a catalyst for social movements. during the conversation, jeremy cites examples of how new power is being leveraged in the world around us and it's powerful impact on creating change. listen at http://bit.ly/jeremyheimans- or tap the link in our bio.
„Éª„Éª„Éª

text:
my father passed away on this day 13 years ago. nothing on earth would heal my heart more than hearing his voice one more time. my father was a pastor and served this country's armed forces. on the back of the book gold mouth, you will find this very tribute. every time i crush a goal or secure a bag, i remind myself of who i'm doing this all for. -
'nothing lasts forever' was one thing my father always used to tell me, and i always remind myself of this when going through challenges in life... i also use this quote to remind myself that no one lives forever, and no moment can last forever, so enjoy and cherish them all. ‚ù§Ô∏è

text:
i used to believe that my healing journey had to be walked independently through the recesses of my heart and wounds. that i alone had to forge through the rubble of my past hurts and choices. i believed i had to stand alone in my wholeness in order to be eligible to be loved wholly. i stand corrected! it is in the offering of shattered pieces and the open hands to receive them that we work together for wholeness. we were never meant to walk this journey alone but to bear one another‚Äôs burdens, to sharpen one another and to unconditionally forgive and love one another. it is through this process that my healing journey has taken flight! i‚Äôm thankful to all the hands that have opened up and held my shattered pieces. i also am thankful for those of you who have laid your shattered pieces into my hands. may we always honor one another‚Äôs journey and extend grace, mercy and love at every opportunity!‚ù§Ô∏è‚ù§Ô∏è‚ù§Ô∏è

text: trigger warning: several years ago i started speaking out publicly about my sexual abuse. that included a curatorial project - ‚Äòsex crimes against black girls‚Äô that was prompted by a hortense spillers essay. doing this work is not easy. not as a survivor trying to hold space for yourself and damn sure not as s survivor trying to hold space for so many other people. despite the fact that @taranajaneen created #metoo to focus on sexual assault against black girls, the most vulnerable group in our community, many others have attempted to co-opt the movement and make it about  sexual assault in the work place, and largely about white women survivors, particularly in hollywood. i‚Äôm so happy that her work  continues to focus on us and our little girls. those who don‚Äôt have voices or platforms, whose names no one knows.  i‚Äôm equally as excited for my big sis #dreamhampton who has always been my spirit animal. she has always gone where no woman or man has dared to go. i can‚Äôt imagine the kind of courage it‚Äôs taken to put this documentary out for public consumption but she‚Äôs done it anyway. robert kelly has got to fucking go. he is a demon. he continues to make money off of black people who rather step in the name of love than demand that his bitch ass be put under the jail. i‚Äôll be tuning into this three part series on @lifetimetv. i encourage you to do the same. sending love to all survivors everywhere and those of us who are doing this very hard work ... of trying to keep us safe, healed and free. @survivingrkelly fuck r. kelly. stop playing his music. stop victim blaming. believe survivors. hold men and abusers accountable. #survivingrkelly

text:
"feminism isn't about making women stronger. women are already strong. it's about changing the way the world perceives that strength."
.
.
.
there was a short time in my life when i denied being a feminist. i chose to call myself a humanist instead.
.
i did for those foolish minutes believe that feminism was about pointing fingers. but i was wrong. feminism is about standing up for yourself. cause no one else will. cause sometimes when you are a woman, you aren't treated as human.
.
tell you the truth--i was scared cause i had finally found a man i loved. and i had married that man. in a weird way that doesn't make sense to me now--i thought being a feminist made me feel thankless for having him in my life.
.
then i moved countries and transferred to a visa that made working as an immigrant woman of color difficult for me. so difficult that it questioned my purpose in life. and all the bull i had been telling myself--about not being a feminist went out the window.
.
i own it now. i say i am a feminist--loud and proud. for no other reason but the sound of it is like a battle cry that gives me hope.
.
.
.

text:
start the year off by doing things differently than the year before. instead of beating our bodies, brains, and taste bud into submissionü§£ ....
we can start to become of aware of what the body needs.

we are offering our cravings handout virtually!! this handout & it's content has helped thousands. we know it will help you too. cravings like sugar hijacks the brain & leaves ones powerless with incredible chemical experiences that make it difficult to stop or even limit the harmful indulgence.  i have been there at 50 lbs over weight, high pressure, kidney masses, and childhood of abuse i had it all. #metoo
food filled a void for me but no matter how bad or hard i worked for the body and mood i wanted i couldn't seem to conquer it. i felt weak, defeated, & depressed, but soon all that changed.  i learned what got in the way of reaching my goals. the driving force for was cravingsü§îüî•food wasn't master over me it was something greater...ü§Ø when i made the connection and understood how my cravings had been a major reason for keeping me feeling stuck and frustrated year after year, i released all guilt blame and shame.
 i gave myself a true fighting chance. #awareness

i want you to have that chance to start over with a renewed perspective of why mastering cravings takes alot more than just simple will power. this handout will not only provide you with what your cravings mean & make it clear as to why losing weight has been a challenge but it will also entail mouth watering recipes to indulge in. 
these recipes wont add to your waistline or store unhealthy fat but instead they will give you energy and comfort that you can share with your family and friends. we want to help those ready and willing to make a difference in their health and that starts by-

#1 being aware of the ways the body talks to us via cravings.

#2 the body does everything to maintain balance.

by downloading this handout you will be able to reduce- * excess bloating * decrease fatigue * confusion
*frustration
*weight gain  find out what your cravings mean and download your handout today for 2019

text: this story was submitted to the survivor tree project by a courageous young survivor named alyssa. alyssa bravely told me how she was betrayed by a friend of hers at the age of 15: a much older man had shown interest in her, and alyssa‚Äôs friend promised him that he could do what he wanted to her. her friend then locked them in a room together, where he assaulted her. alyssa: in your submission, you thanked me for allowing you to tell your story. it‚Äôs me who should be thanking you, fellow survivor. it takes the mightiest, strongest kind of bravery to do what you did and speak your truth, and i wish i could meet you and give you the biggest hug and thank you in person. i know you have been blamed and shamed for what happened, and i‚Äôm so sorry. it was not your fault. and because it was not your fault, you know what? you don‚Äôt have to accept the blame. you don‚Äôt have to accept the shame. reject it. i want you to repeat to yourself, out loud, ‚Äúthis was not my fault! i did nothing wrong!‚Äù again. and again. and again. until these words come as easily as your own name and simply roll off your tongue the next time you face the vultures. they may not like your new-found confidence. they may push back, may blame you even more. don‚Äôt. back. down. the reason they push is that they are afraid of you. the reason they blame is that they don‚Äôt want you to realize that you are powerful. because they know that once you realize that, they‚Äôve lost. these are your words. this is your story. you‚Äôre in charge. you‚Äôve got this, alyssa. you‚Äôre already winning. ‚ú®üå± click the link in my bio if others would like to contribute your story to the survivor tree project. #selflove #love #survivor #survivoradvocate #survivorselfcare #believesurvivors #believewomen #believeblackwomen #rapesurvivor #metoo #timesup #endrapeculture #metoomovement #thesurvivortreeproject #artist
name: Mel Hanley | Survivor Advocate

text:
variety posted an article today outlining the findings of a university calculating the female presence in hollywood in 2018. with gender equality at the forefront of the social conversation last year, many people expected to see a larger margin of change. instead, only 8% of directors of last year's films were women. now, i know some incredible male directors and i would do anything to support them. i'm not interested in putting them down or taking away their opportunities. however, as a female and a director, i do hope for a more balanced industry. i hope that young girls who dream of making films do not see these numbers and despair. and i hope those with the power to hire and change these statistics will find ways to do so that not only improve equality, but also create even more innovative and meaningful content. and i will say this only once because it should not have to be said at all: there is no shortage of qualified, impressive, or marketable female directors. i am posting this not for antagonistic reasons but to remind us all that simply because an issue is raised to the public eye does not mean we have arrived at change. change comes with time and effort and people choosing to question the status quo. let us take up a that mantel, not just in this issue but in so many more, so that this world may become a better place for us all. ¬∑ ¬∑ ¬∑ 
the full article (and a link to the study's findings) can be found in my bio.

text:
bettina arndt is a rare public voice speaking on behalf of men ‚Äì and the women who love them.

this respected social commentator is renowned for tackling unmentionable topics. a former clinical psychologist and one of australia‚Äôs first sex therapist, she first became well-known for breaking down taboos about talking about sex.

now it is men‚Äôs lives we aren‚Äôt allowed to speak about ‚Äì the very real problems confronting men and boys in our male-bashing society. #mentoo breaks the silence about what it means to be a man in australia today.

text:
keluarga adalah segalanya bagi king of bollywood, shah rukh khan. sementara banyak pasangan seleb bollywood lain bercerai, shah rukh khan dan istrinya gauri khan sudah melewati 30 tahun pernikahan.

mereka masih saling jatuh cinta seperti saat bertemu kali pertama. kunci dari semua itu adalah menghargai satu sama lain lebih dari apa pun.

seperti wawancara terakhirnya dengan the indian express, perlakuan aktor kuch kuch hota hai itu pada istrinya sukses bikin penggemar meleleh. shah rukh khan ngaku kalau selama 30 tahun menikah, doi nggak pernah lancang buka-buka dompet sang istri.

hal itu juga dia ajarkan pada anak lelakinya, aryan yang menginjak 21 tahun. sudah sepantasnya lelaki menghormati hak perempuan.
.
''saya mengajari putra saya yang berusia 21 tahun bahwa tidak menghormati seseorang adalah perbuatan tidak baik. itulah sebenarnya inti gerakan #metoo. saya berbicara tentang rasa hormat dasar. saya sudah menikah selama 30 tahun, tapi saya belum pernah membuka dompet istri saya. saya masih mengetuk pintu kamar jika dia ganti baju. saya juga terbiasa mengetuk pintu kamar anak perempuan saya sebelum masuk. mereka tahu saya yang mengetuk, tapi itu adalah ruang privasi mereka,'' kata shah rukh khan yang dilansir dari bollywoodshaadis.com.
.
''tiga hal yang penting adalah menghormati, menghormati, dan menghormati. saya sangat percaya itu. beberapa teman wanita saya yang saya kenal selama bertahun-tahun, kadang-kadang menganggap saya terlalu formal. tapi tidak mungkin ada cinta dan romansa tanpa rasa hormat. menghormati berarti kesetaraan. ini adalah apa yang telah saya lakukan dengan istri dan teman-teman wanita saya karena saya benar-benar mencintai mereka,'' lanjut shah rukh khan.
.
''istri saya adalah prioritas utama. dengan yakin saya bilang jika saya diminta membuat pilihan antara karier dan gauri, saya akan meninggalkan film. saya mungkin saja jadi gila, tapi demi dia saya rela. gauri satu-satunya yang saya miliki. saya mencintainya,'' tutup shah rukh khan.

manis banget kan perlakuan shah rukh khan pada istrinya? ada yang meleleh?

source : matamata

#srk #shahrukhkhan

"the announcement comes nearly two months after a federal complaint was filed against the ivy league school by seven current and former graduate students who allege three professors created a toxic environment where female subjects were routinely subjected to sexual harassment and even rape.

text:
34 states in the u.s where police can legally rape suspects in custody. we await to see what policies the progressive candidates and parties will enact into the 116th legislative congress, and fully acknowledge (via bipartisanship) h.r.6568 "closing the law enforcement consent loophole act of 2018 115th congress"(2017-2018). a bill that would make it illegal for federal law enforcement officers to have sex or rape suspects in custody. this is something that should be pushed locally and regionally, but we are still questioning any inhibitions and aversions that prolongs this from being on the national parties agendas. 
law enforcement officers and police unions are not met with severe opposition from political leaders and parties on the ballot, which further suggests that protecting the interests of the ruling-class is priority. if you know where leo and congress stands on police abuse, misconduct, and sexual assault, how can we truly say that we are crystal clear on which direction is best for all voters in the country--before, during and after the trump era? the plebiscites between a wall and a fiscal budget has created another fiasco, oblivious to a political agenda protecting the rights of suspects(in custody), and removing special protections from officers who abuse their powers on/off duty.
#statevsusmag #police #corruption #government #policebrutality #rape #sexualassault #metoo

text:
p.s.a

i will take this down in the morning,  cuz the way my energy is set up, i keep certain things intentionally out my psyche.  i know this #survivingrkelly is trending now, it is all i see up and down my timeline. in no way is my intentional avoidance of it agreeing with, giving permission or whateva, it is simply me , social worker who hear enough stories on a daily basis, to know how to protect myself.  with that said, if you are watching or plan to watch, please be mindful of how you internalize the stories. please also have your strategies in place if you are a survivor because secondary ptsd or vicarious traumatization is real.  i know some of the stories, but refuse to watch it. he needs help and so do those women! #mentalhealth #mentalhealthmatters
name: Not So Obscure

p.s.a

i will take this down in the morning,  cuz the way my energy is set up, i keep certain things intentionally out my psyche.  i know this #survivingrkelly is trending now, it is all i see up and down my timeline. in no way is my intentional avoidance of it agreeing with, giving permission or whateva, it is simply me , social worker who hear enough stories on a daily basis, to know how to protect myself.  with that said, if you are watching or plan to watch, please be mindful of how you internalize the stories. please also have your strategies in place if you are a survivor because secondary ptsd or vicarious traumatization is real.  i know some of the stories, but refuse to watch it. he needs help and so do those women! #mentalhealth #mentalhealthmatters

text:
growing up i didnt really know what ‚Äòfeminism‚Äô was & some of the 1st intros to the word were the media‚Äôs misrepresentations of its sterotypes (cue wild haired bra burning ‚Äúcrazy‚Äù women ‚Ä¶ barf)
in a nutshell feminism is: equality for everyone.
pretty simple right? apparently not‚Ä¶ a lot of people are up in arms about current feminist movements like times up, #metoo, the gender wage gap. somehow along the lines ‚Äúequality for all‚Äù it became ‚Äúwomen want it all & men get none‚Äù - sorry what? 
the topic of feminism is a huuuuuge conversation with so many complexities, but i wanted to highlight some myth busting reminders:
üå∏anyone can be a feminist - its not just for women because (surprise) it‚Äôs about equality for all
üå∏while it focuses on women‚Äôs rights, it *should* be intersectional - equality for all genders/identities/orientations/races/economic statuses/etc while also recognizing systems of oppression & discrimination, how they intersect & how we can work to dismantle them!
üå∏being a feminist doesn‚Äôt mean you hate men, so stop. equal rights does not mean less to another person - it‚Äôs not pie! 
it also doesn‚Äôt mean that you hate ‚Äúfeminine‚Äù things/roles - these are stereotypes! feminism is literally about being whoever you want to be & being accepted for it! üå∏feminism is about all genders being able to express themselves & be respected - including men - it‚Äôs about breaking down gender roles & inequality, that men also face! üå∏feminists (women‚Ä¶) are often called crazy/loud/bossy/bitchy/etc which only perpetuates the stereotypes & diminishes the hard work being done towards equality. sure, some of us are a little mad about it. but don‚Äôt discredit us. also, this only continues a patriarchal society in which women are not valued.
üå∑i feminism can mean different things for different people. there are a million different ways in which people will identify with feminism & incorporate it into their lives.
üíïshoutout to the rad guys in my life that have engaged in convos about feminism - i appreciate your honesty & willingness to learn üå∏

the topic of feminism is a huuuuuge conversation with so many complexities, but i wanted to highlight some myth busting reminders:
üå∏anyone can be a feminist - its not just for women because (surprise) it‚Äôs about equality for all
üå∏while it focuses on women‚Äôs rights, it *should* be intersectional - equality for all genders/identities/orientations/races/economic statuses/etc while also recognizing systems of oppression & discrimination, how they intersect & how we can work to dismantle them!
üå∏being a feminist doesn‚Äôt mean you hate men, so stop. equal rights does not mean less to another person - it‚Äôs not pie! 
it also doesn‚Äôt mean that you hate ‚Äúfeminine‚Äù things/roles - these are stereotypes! feminism is literally about being whoever you want to be & being accepted for it! üå∏feminism is about all genders being able to express themselves & be respected - including men - it‚Äôs about breaking down gender roles & inequality, that men also face! üå∏feminists (women‚Ä¶) are often called crazy/loud/bossy/bitchy/etc which only perpetuates the stereotypes & diminishes the hard work being done towards equality. sure, some of us are a little mad about it. but don‚Äôt discredit us. also, this only continues a patriarchal society in which women are not valued.
üå∑i feminism can mean different things for different people. there are a million different ways in which people will identify with feminism & incorporate it into their lives.
üíïshoutout to the rad guys in my life that have engaged in convos about feminism - i appreciate your honesty & willingness to learn üå∏

text:
inner calling - as children we know. we are able to think about ourselves this clearly. we know our likes and dislikes, wants, needs, desires, and general purpose. we know ourselves fully, until we take too many of other people‚Äôs thoughts about us inside, mistaking their thoughts for our truth. üó£
.
the brave few who don‚Äôt allow the static and noise of other‚Äôs views to penetrate inside themselves and manage to follow their earliest inner calling lead lives others envy and often want for themselves. ‚≠êÔ∏è
.
on the whim and delight of my inner child, i picked up a used eddie money vinyl the last time i was at @amoebahollywood üé∂ my family wasn‚Äôt wealthy growing up. i had few toys, but i was rich with records and allowed free range with the turn table. i had this record and played it what feels like a million times back in the day. üéµ .
to my adult surprise while taking it out to play once home, the inner lining had this quote. i didn‚Äôt remember it striking me as a child or even that it was there, but it hit to the heart of adult me, and this mission of advocacy and education i am finding myself on these days. the inner child in me knew my calling included having an audience and a voice. i‚Äôm not sure where i‚Äôm headed just yet; however, every day i am reminding myself to bask in the joys of the ride as i honor and step into the light of my earliest inner calling, which i now know includes taking my life experiences and teaching skills to a new level. ‚ù§Ô∏è
.
my deepest wish is that all people reading this would stop just for a moment to ask their inner child to speak up, cut the static, and brave the ride of coming into fruition. the world needs our lights to shine. let‚Äôs show up. üåé
.

an updated edition of the sunday times bestseller britain's best-known classicist mary beard, is also a committed and vocal feminist. with wry wit, she revisits the gender agenda and shows how history has treated powerful women. her examples range from the classical world to the modern day, from medusa and athena to theresa may and hillary clinton. beard explores the cultural underpinnings of misogyny, considering the public voice of women, our cultural assumptions about women's relationship with power, and how powerful women resist being packaged into a male template. a year on since the advent of #metoo, beard looks at how the discussions have moved on during this time, and how that intersects with issues of rape and consent, and the stories men tell themselves to support their actions. in trademark beardian style, using examples ancient and modern, beard argues, 'it's time for change - and now!' from the author of international bestseller spqr: a history of ancient rome.

üáªüá™ asistir a un taller sobre la importancia del lenguaje inclusivo en el lugar de trabajo fue una experiencia que cambi√≥ mi vida. de hecho, a√∫n me mantengo en contacto con algunas de las personas que conoc√≠ durante aquella ocasi√≥n en @unfpa y, precisamente, la autenticidad y la vulnerabilidad son las piedras angulares de nuestra amistad digital. ese d√≠a, fue una de las primeras veces en mi vida que me atrev√≠ a hablar en voz alta sobre ser un sobreviviente de asalto sexual. sentir que eres due√±o de tu historia cambia la forma en que te relacionas contigo mismo y es una actitud que te ayuda a sentirte empoderado, e irte alejando de todos los sentimientos negativos (o al menos, comenzar a tener plena consciencia de ellos y tomar medidas para aprender a canalizarlos sanamente).
.
üá∫üá∏ attending to a workshop about the importance of inclusive language at the workplace was a life changing experience for me. i keep in touch with some of the people i met back then at @unfpa and i must say that #authenticity and #vulnerability are the cornerstones of our digital friendship. it was one of the first times in my life that i dared to speak out loud about being a sexual assault survivor. feeling that you own your story changes the way you relate with yourself, and it‚Äôs an attitude that helps you feel empowered and move away from all negative feelings (...or at least, it makes you begin to be fully aware of them and take steps to learn how to channel your emotions in a healthier way).

text:
the mission of iwash (industry women against sexual harassment) is to create the awareness of women in the bar and restaurant industry who face the struggles of being sexually harassed by patrons, co-workers, managers, and owners. this awareness campaign has a mission to improve the status of the 90 percent of women who have been reported to being a victim by giving them the opportunity to speak without shame. our mission is to give industry women a voice so that ultimately we can create safety and professionalism in our work environment amongst colleagues, patrons, and employers.  women play a vital roll in this industry and if we lose them due to such a non tolerable act, businesses could face potential failure. iwash welcomes all women to share their stories so that this community can understand the severity of this subject that has been held quiet for too long. üôåüèΩ

the open slate by radhika is proud to bring to you our very own picks of the best things to have happened to the people of ahmedabad this year!
.
.
1. our city experienced fashion like never before, ranging from the white crow store, offering the most chic menswear, to story of india, embracing all that is indian and elegant, to our very own h&m, finally!

2. exotic cuisines found their way to ahmedabad this year and how! sante spa cuisine, deliciously reminding us to choose healthy, organic ingredients, kuro, for the most authentic, tantalising japanese culinary experiences respectively, rangeen, with its ever-evolving offerings, a fusion of traditional and novel and little french house, for its chicago-style deep dish pizza, definitely created foodgasmic memories for us in 2018.

3. opening with one of the best art shows of the year, 079 stories has us intrigued and excited, as the city‚Äôs latest gorgeous artscape. we can‚Äôt wait to see the opportunities, events and gatherings it brings to us in 2019!

4. 2018 has been the year of the #metoo movement with ahmedabad also seeing its first #metoo meet, and as an year dedicated to women having an amplified voice, it would be a shame to not mention the fabulous women writers‚Äô fest, the first of its kind in ahmedabad, which brought some of the most brilliant female icons upfront and candid with our ahmedabadi audience.

5. in a city that has given birth to some incredible designers, our pick this year is malav sanghavi, an nid alumnus who created lifecradle, the only ever baby incubator to have been created out of cardboard and has been featured in forbes india‚Äôs 30 under 30 list!
.
.
these were our bright spots in 2018, do tell us what were yours?

text:
john legend is one of the few stars speaking out in lifetime‚Äôs new documentary titled surviving r. kelly.
.
the shocking 6-part docuseries features wide-ranging interviews with r. kelly‚Äôs family members, former friends and colleagues, but most notably, women who claim that for decades the hit-making singer and producer used his power and influence to sexually and physically abuse women and young girls.
.
‚Äúr. kelly has brought so much pain to so many people‚Äù legend, 40, said¬†during an interview for the documentary. legend has openly supported women‚Äôs right‚Äôs organization time‚Äôs up and the #muterkelly boycott.
.
throughout the documentary legend shares reflections on kelly throughout the years. recalling the singer‚Äôs biggest hit off of the 1996 space jam soundtrack, legend says ‚Äú‚Äòi believe i can fly‚Äô is a powerful song and it inspired a lot of people. it was just massive.‚Äù
.
legend is the only major performer speaking out in the documentary but he is not the only prominent figure who takes part. wendy williams is interviewed along with founder of the #metoo movement tarana burke and popular radio hosts charlamagne tha god and tom joyner. chance the rapper also makes a brief appearance, voicing regret for working with kelly amid the recent allegations.
#mahnlikegoro

text:
dear you,üíúüíúüíú
-
just because you‚Äôve escaped familiar abuse does not mean any other form of abuse is tolerable. what may look like better isn‚Äôt better if you still have to protect the actions of whomever is causing any emotional, physical, mental, or sexual abuse towards you. -

an abuser only abuses when they think their actions are acceptable. breaking the silence removes power from the abuser and allows the opportunity for your own healing. -

if you or any one you know is suffering in silence share this post taking the pledge against domestic violence using #ispeakdv as the caption. -

only by our words can we expose and honor those voices that have suffered in silence long enough. #ispeakdv #whodoyouspeakfor -

i will create a peaceful and safe environment in my home; and will not raise my hand in violence nor my voice in anger.

by living this pledge, i am joining with others to end violence in all homes and community.
#ispeakdv

text:
lifetime‚Äôs docuseries surviving r. kelly debuted on thursday night. the show, which runs through saturday, documents decades of alleged abusive behavior by the singer through dozens of interviews with survivors, siblings, associates, experts, critics, and performers.

the first two episodes focused on the beginning of kelly‚Äôs career and the peak of his mega-stardom, ending just before the 2002 sex tape that would lead to his trial (and ultimate acquittal). it has harrowing first-person accounts of alleged physical abuse, controlling and manipulative behavior, nonconsensual taping of sexual encounters, and much, much more.

across the nation, women and men have called for justice ‚Äì glorified sex trafficking fundraisers ‚Äì rooted in public disgust for kelly‚Äôs use of sexual manipulation, abuse, harassment, and coercion of young black women.

#nomore #breakingthesilence #timesup #survivingrkelly #childabuseawareness #metoo

this, is what being dependent feels like.
.
"here let me tell you how to do it."
"the pain from periods can't be that bad!". "why aren't you fasting?".
"why isn't she praying mum?".
"all you do is eat, cut down some fat, pig."
. "all you have are bones, eat something."
. "that dress makes you look pale/tan."
. "you are not supposed to ride a bicycle after you turn 10."
"there's too much salt in this, make me a new one."
"you should have covered yourself properly, see he's looking at you as if you're a walking prey."
"why didn't you fight him back?" .

maya angelou (april 4, 1929 - may 28, 2014) was an american poet, singer, memoirist, and civil rights activist. an incredible writer, she published seven autobiographies, three books of essay and several books of poetry. she received dozens of awards and more than 50 honorary degrees. her critically acclaimed autobiography, i know why the caged bird sings (1969), tells of her life up to the age of 17 in a stunning (brutal) honesty almost unknown for that time. despite the publishing world‚Äôs prejudices that ‚Äúblack women‚Äôs lives were rarely worthy of autobiography‚Äù, angelou‚Äôs book became a best seller and was, and is still, widely taught in schools. ‚Äúyou may shoot me with your words, 
you may cut me with your eyes,
you may kill me with your hatefulness,
but still, like air, i‚Äôll rise‚Äù. [poem- still i rise]

text:
back to basics.

ive juggled with the concept of social media. ive tried to figure out what my soul and spirit feels in terms of ego with platforms such as instagram...what i know for sure is that i dont want to fuel self-obsession, but i do want to promote self-love, self-care and the things which bring me joy and happiness.

i continue to explore my journey with social media and the positive interaction it can be for the world. we have to express ourselves. we have to love ourselves. we have to examine our messages and our intentions if we are at all concerned about making the world a better and more loving place. we have to encourage and suppprt each others journey. ive personally been on and off...deleting accounts and forming new ones. i continue to evolve in my own exploration of who i am and what my purpose here is.

there has always been an undercurrent of sexual abuse of black girls in our community and the adults who refuse to talk about and or admit their involvement in it. just like mental health issues, these sexual assaults are swept under the rug and voices are silenced. last nights #survivingrkelly shed some light on the 25 years of the mental, physical and emotional enslavement and abuse of so many young girls, often only a child at the onset of meeting r kelly. 
parts 1&2 aired last night and parts 3&4 air tonight. 
we need to protect our young black girls at all costs!

text:
*journal moments* #whygirls

so here‚Äôs my solution-because while i applaud the increased awareness, the pointless rhetoric & the pointing of fingers still doesn‚Äôt get us any further towards a strategy to solve the societal ills towards & harsh realities of our girls that doesn‚Äôt just happen in private studios or on tour buses, but also back rooms of houses, stairwells in schools across the country, on the vicious streets in our neighborhoods and must we not forget, storage closets & offices in churches.... it‚Äôs been the vision and it‚Äôs been my why...
girls need their own space in which they can flourish and thrive, be developed & taught, cultivated & nurtured, and helped to maneuver through a world that‚Äôs absent of some fathers, disconnected with some of today‚Äôs moms and void of a systematic attempt to ensure girls have a freakin‚Äô chance regardless of background, status, race, creed or color. and this offering shouldn‚Äôt be predicated on whether or not you‚Äôre one of the few ‚Äúprivileged‚Äù or not. that‚Äôs a fool. death to the day that only if you have money can you have a chance at better! 
memphis!! your posts mean nothing if nothing occurring makes you act.... but i do understand-god gives the vision to those who it‚Äôs divinely designed for-
so i appreciate the #metoo movement, the truth movement we see happening and the raised awareness around gender inequities, disparities and the overall view of the ‚Äúgirl‚Äù in this country-especially the ‚Äúethnic girl....‚Äù thanks again for the confirmation of my ‚Äúwhy....‚Äù i hear you god. i‚Äôll take it and continue to run with it. i won‚Äôt just make a post and stop there. i‚Äôll create an entire path solely for girls, that just doesn‚Äôt begin and end with after school programs, weekend mentorship or an occasional workshop but what if we combined all of those necessary happenings full-time coupled with academic & intellectual development with the support of women anywhere & everywhere-because one thing is for certain women-you were indeed once a girl.....now wouldn‚Äôt that be something.... #visioncasting 
thanks god for the consistent reminder of why....
#whygirls 
will you be at the table?? see you in 2 weeks memphis!

tweet_full:
*journal moments* #whygirls

so here‚Äôs my solution-because while i applaud the increased awareness, the pointless rhetoric & the pointing of fingers still doesn‚Äôt get us any further towards a strategy to solve the societal ills towards & harsh realities of our girls that doesn‚Äôt just happen in private studios or on tour buses, but also back rooms of houses, stairwells in schools across the country, on the vicious streets in our neighborhoods and must we not forget, storage closets & offices in churches.... it‚Äôs been the vision and it‚Äôs been my why...
girls need their own space in which they can flourish and thrive, be developed & taught, cultivated & nurtured, and helped to maneuver through a world that‚Äôs absent of some fathers, disconnected with some of today‚Äôs moms and void of a systematic attempt to ensure girls have a freakin‚Äô chance regardless of background, status, race, creed or color. and this offering shouldn‚Äôt be predicated on whether or not you‚Äôre one of the few ‚Äúprivileged‚Äù or not. that‚Äôs a fool. death to the day that only if you have money can you have a chance at better! 
memphis!! your posts mean nothing if nothing occurring makes you act.... but i do understand-god gives the vision to those who it‚Äôs divinely designed for-
so i appreciate the #metoo movement, the truth movement we see happening and the raised awareness around gender inequities, disparities and the overall view of the ‚Äúgirl‚Äù in this country-especially the ‚Äúethnic girl....‚Äù thanks again for the confirmation of my ‚Äúwhy....‚Äù i hear you god. i‚Äôll take it and continue to run with it. i won‚Äôt just make a post and stop there. i‚Äôll create an entire path solely for girls, that just doesn‚Äôt begin and end with after school programs, weekend mentorship or an occasional workshop but what if we combined all of those necessary happenings full-time coupled with academic & intellectual development with the support of women anywhere & everywhere-because one thing is for certain women-you were indeed once a girl.....now wouldn‚Äôt that be something.... #visioncasting 
thanks god for the consistent reminder of why....

text:
when i was 17 years old, i was sexually assaulted at work by a co worker who was  utterly obsessed with me... it started off with him doing nice gestures like buying me lunch at work... then turned into lingerie gifts & jewelry, then to begging me to marry him because he couldn't ‚Äústop thinking about me.‚Äù - all gifts and concerns were reported & given to management/hr... & all were downplayed with ‚Äúoh he‚Äôs just being nice‚Äù smh.. i even had to beg them to stop putting us to work together because it got more & more uncomfortable & even that was ignored until one day... he came into a room i was in, pushed me on the bed and groped my ass & tits.. no i wasn‚Äôt silent about it when it happened! i went ham on him, hr & everyone else who tried to calm me down. i wanted to press charges right away... didn‚Äôt even wait for them to call the police, i called myself. but when the police arrived, they went to the general manager of the hotel before they spoke to me. after speaking with management they all came to me at once & freaking manipulated me by telling me it would take years for my trail to be over, offered me weeks off with paid vacation, a raise and told me they would just terminate him... or if i press chargers, he would keep his job & i would lose mine until the trial was over... me being 17 with no true guidance on how to go about this & having my own apartment & bills to pay... guess what i did because of my circumstances?! i shut up! & took the time off- thinking i was going to flourish in my hospitality career. smh!

yes my mom knew, & yes i wish she would have pushed me to follow through but i was so adamant about excelling in the industry, ‚Äúi let it go‚Äù & soon after i agreed, the entire management team left the property & the deal was off! my offender was gone but i was still angry... still get angry when i‚Äôm reminded of it & when ignorant people say shit like ‚Äúit‚Äôs too late‚Äù for women to ‚Äúbring up‚Äù their sexual harassment stories.. fck y‚Äôall! it's never too late to speak up! no matter how long it takes them or how ‚Äúsmall‚Äù or ‚Äúless severe‚Äù y‚Äôall think a case is. hurt is hurt. wrong is wrong. a predator is a fucking predator no matter how talented he/she is!

text:
2018 has been a roller coaster ride for the oppressed and the oppressor, for the helpless and the powerful and for the campaigners and the bashers. from marital rape to homosexuality to #metoo we have come a long way. let us have a look at some of the most important events that india witnessed this year.

#3 same-sex intercourse, no longer criminal

the decriminalization of homosexuality was yet another landmark judgment that proved that we as a society need to grow up and not poke our nose into what two consenting adults do with each other within their four walls. the court advocated that lgbt community possesses human rights like all other sections of society. equality is the essence of the constitution and 377 is arbitrary. a person‚Äôs sexuality is not unnatural, but a part of their personality. no person should suffer from the shrouds of disdain for their sexual preferences. however, as of now, only so-called ‚Äúunnatural‚Äù sex within the same sex is decriminalized. it is just the beginning to a long battle where homosexuals are happily accepted and treated as equals and same-sex marriages are not frowned upon.

text:
(cnn) psychological and emotional abuse in intimate relationships is now a crime in ireland.

the domestic violence act 2018 went into effect on tuesday and provides new protections for victims of "coercive control," a type of emotional and psychological abuse aimed at stripping a person of their self-worth and agency.

although psychological and emotional abuse -- including controlling behavior, isolation, and threats of violence -- can be more difficult to recognize than physical violence, it can be just as damaging, experts say.

ireland's minister of justice and equality charlie flanagan said in a statement wednesday that the new law "recognizes that the effect of non-violent control in an intimate relationship can be as harmful to victims as physical abuse because it is an abuse of the unique trust associated with an intimate relationship." "this new provision sends a message that society will no longer tolerate the appalling breach of trust committed by one partner against the other in an intimate context," he added.

in a 2014 european union agency for fundamental rights (fra) pan-european survey on violence against women, almost a third of irish women (31%) said they had experienced psychological abuse by a partner. a further 23% of respondents said they had experienced controlling behavior, 24% said they had experienced abusive behavior, and 12% said they had experienced stalking (including online stalking). women's aid, ireland's national domestic violence support organization, said that while it welcomed the new law, in order for it to be effective, it must be properly resourced. "it must be positive, it must be practical and it must make them and their children safer from abuse. what is promised on paper must be fully resourced to be effective in protecting those affected by domestic violence. we are concerned that an already over-stretched system will see an increase in demand when the new provisions commence," margaret martin, women's aid director, said in a statement on monday.

full story: https://www.cnn.com/2019/01/02/health/ireland-coercive-control-domestic-abuse-intl/index.html

text:
the (hash)#metoo movement is #empowering #victims of #sexual #assault to speak up like never before, but what should be a watershed moment for holding #assailants accountable has coincided with a troubling trend: #police departments in the #us are becoming less and less likely to successfully close #rape #investigations.

the so-called ‚Äúclearance rate‚Äù for #rape cases fell last year to its lowest point since at least the 1960s, according to #fbi #data provided to the #associated #press. that nadir may be driven, at least in part, by a greater willingness by police to correctly classify rape cases and leave them open even when there is little hope of solving them.
.
.
but #experts say it also reflects the fact that not enough resources are being devoted to investigating sexual assault at a time when more victims are entrusting #police with their harrowing experiences.
.
.
‚Äúthis is the second-most serious crime in the fbi's #crime #index,‚Äù said carol tracy, executive director of the women's law project in #philadelphia, ‚Äúand it simply doesn't get the necessary resources from police.‚Äù
.
.
police successfully closed just 32 percent of rape investigations nationwide in 2017, according to the data, ranking it second only to #robbery as the least-solved #violent crime. that statistic is down from about 62 percent in 1964, despite advances such as #dna testing.
.
.
the fbi provided the #ap with a dataset of rape statistics dating back to the early 1960s - a table that includes more complete data than the snapshot the bureau releases each fall.
.
.
the grim report card has prompted debate among criminal #justice experts, with some attributing the falling clearance rate to an antiquated approach to investigations...
.
.
.
.

text:
it's not easy to shut the negativity around you but you can try. life could be a lot easier when you learn to see passing the fake and plastic characters. people can't see you owning things that they believe it's out of their reach. so, when someone pass a negative comment on you, take a deep breath and move on. yes, it hurts. i've been there too. i know the darkness and the chill a continuous hatered comment can bring to you but remember you are not here to live their capabilities but yours. only you can set bar for yourself. don't let others to install your limitations. .
real beauty & strength reside in you. listen to your inner voice. it's always calm, loving and peaceful. however, it can easily contaminate by the outside noises.
.
escape the outer negativity and fall in love with yourself. believe in you and the whisper inside you. .
promise yourself that you will give freedom to the voice inside you to speak and live!
.
be free, be you!
#fearlessfeminine

text:
dare you not ask a mother about 
grief. she has the silence 
of broken homes
stuffed down her throat.
and my poetry 
pokes my mother right 
in the belly. 
in my body anger mob lynched 
hope, 
hope that mob lynches 
pain. 
your hurt against my 
heart is like diamond
against milk teeth
so i'll take mine and leave. 
i locked all my doors and 
forgot the keys.
your skies may launch 
fists upon my roof but 
forgiveness is the 
sharpest weapon 
that you could kill me with. 
praying is a weapon 
i never learnt to to use 
after all how do you 
fight the softness in 
a mother's wrath? 
art is a city 
for all us crazy kamikazes 
and i have lost my way home. 
only fire can be home for fire 
so i burnt everything 
looking for mine [ home ]. there are no exits from here 
and no more doors left to open. 
the women here 
have passed on injustice 
mother to daughter 
like a secret recipe only 
women can feast upon 
and i want everything in 
my mother's plate. 
my family name 
is baggage i couldn't carry 
tell my father 
my throat collapsed 
halfway through 365 apologies.

i hope you never see your 
mother cry, 
her softness is bittersweet,
bitter, mostly. 
i took refuge under silence and 
i know everything i didn't say 
slit her heart then mine. 
i peeked into my tomorrow 
and saw my yesterday burning.

the hurt took with it 
all the bruises.

i know pain has my address 
i'll be ready for it 
when it comes. 
i no longer have excuses.
.
.
utopiangrey.
(@utopiangrey)
.
.
.

text: emotional eating has a bad reputation. but food and the act of eating is purposely intended for self soothing. there is a reason why we want ben & jerry üç¶ when we have gone through a breakup or why in the winter months we crave food with higher fats. our bodies are constantly looking for homeostasis and a sense of regulation. food and what we eat is a part of finding that balance within our bodies system. and often times our mind can‚Äôt make sense of what the body knows it needs to regulate the system and find balance. what is not a part of that balance is diet culture. diet culture and the ways it has tricked us into believing that wanting that chocolate after a long day or pasta üçù on an evening alone is ‚Äúwrong‚Äù. experiencing guilt, shame or self hatred around what we do or do not eat is not natural. it is not a part of the bodies internal wisdom; it is diet culture internalized. ‚úãüèΩ so pause... next time you find yourself eating something for the pure pleasure of it... whatever that is... take a deep breathe and acknowledge that 1) you are listening to your body and 2) you are saying f*ck you to diet culture. because food is meant to be pleasurable and there are 100,000+ reasons to eat and 100,000* thing to try, taste and explore on your eating journey.

text_retweet:
i didn't expect to be so triggered by last night's airing of #survivingrkelly so much that i had to turn away during some segments. with others, i found myself asking "oh that's what that was??" realizing you're a survivor is scary. i had to take steps of protection during the viewing. i'm so glad dream hampton took the necessary steps to fully air out what this serial abuser, r*pist and molester has done largely unquestioned for years, especially because most of his victims are black and brown women.

if during this viewing you feel triggered and unsafe, take time to take care of yourself. your story is no less valid if it's hard to take in others. talk to someone who has been deemed trustworthy by you. keep yourself protected. don't shrink, but stay protected.

#repost from @blackmindsmatterproject with @regram.app ... we must protect and cherish black girls! #survivingrkelly #protectblackwomen #protectblackgirls

#mdgjpodcast 
#muterkelly
#metoo
#believesurvivors

text:
project reflecting on a woman's wish to be seen and her simultaneous impulse to hide herself, after centuries of misogynistic programming.

for centuries, women have been reduced solely to their appearance, their physical beauty deemed their only worth. western philosophers who have shaped our collective thinking -¬†aristotle[i], socrates[ii], jean-jacques rousseau[iii], darwin[iv], schopenhauer[v], nietzsche[vi] -¬†compared women to animals, incapable of rational thought, devoid of intelligence. and although present generations are desperately trying to escape these narrow confinements, the ingrained programming leaves many women struggling with their self-worth.

the objectification of the female body is an effective form of dehumanization. women's sexuality is exploited and suppressed at the same time. admired and reviled, chased and judged, praised and ridiculed.¬†this opppresive societal schizophrenia is mirrored in every woman's soul.

this series reflects on the desire to be seen, coupled with the shame and instinctive need to hide.

_____
the past couple years have been challenging for women, communities of color and lgbtq+ folks. recently we‚Äôve seen increased incidents that may have undermined our sense of safety: attacks on immigrants and the lgbtq community, #metoo reports of epidemic sexual harassment and assault for women in all sectors, as well as a rise in intimate partner violence. safety continues to be a growing concern for many marginalized people. but we are also taking a stand and fighting back, helping each other, and in many cases triumphing as we did during the midterm elections with historic wins for women of color. 
_____
as jiu-jitsu martial artists, we are joining the fight by offering our knowledge to empower and strengthen our community. starting in 2019, sweaty betties and @fourelementsfitness will be joining forces to help end violence against women and girls, particularly among girls and women of color with low to modest means. we are collaborating to offer scholarships to a monthly women‚Äôs self-defense workshops. our goal is to provide free self-defense training for girls and women at four elements fitness in oakland, ca. 
____
sponsorship application for the february women‚Äôs self-defense workshop is open now and the deadline is jan.25. 2019. scholarships are first come, first served basis with limited amount per month. must be girls or women of color and ages 9+ to apply. no experience required to attend workshop. we reserve the right to close applications when full capacity are reached. if you or anyone you know are interested in a life-changing opportunity, please contact us at mollii@fourelementsfitness.com. workshop details below:

text:
untold stories is a piece about domestic violence ‚Ä¢ among the immigrant south asian community specifically domestic abuse is a rampant, silenced epidemic. 2 out of every 5 south asian immigrant women in the u.s. are survivors of domestic violence. with blinding allegiances to ideas of honor and reputation, stigma of divorce, and patriarchy, seeking help is all the more complicated for south asian victims‚Ä¶
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¶which means the solution to help our immigrant south asian community demands to be a multi-pronged strategy. today i would like to introduce to you an incredible organization based in new york working to eradicate domestic violence and shifting the conversation from ‚Äúa private family matter to a public social issue.‚Äù
‚Ä¢
sakhi for south asian women @sakhinyc was founded in 1989 by five south asian women looking to create a safe space to serve survivors and effectively engage in the movement to end violence against women ‚Ä¢ sakhi offers legal assistance in immigration-related matters and a path to citizenship, financial support for educational needs such as nursing school, advocacy in court, culture-sensitive support groups, translation assistance during healthcare visits, legal consultation for access to medical car // see more at www.sakhi.org ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢
for the next few days i will be sharing more about sakhi for south asian women and how you can get involved in helping this movement to eradicate domestic violence and form healthy, stronger communities. ‚ô•

text:
i can't help but smile from ear to ear when i have the opportunity to help others by breaking my silence. 
the topic is serious (child abuse), but the life i live now is full of wonderment. 
i am grateful for every moment of every day - there was a time when i wanted it all to end. i thought to end the pain, i needed to end my life. 
now, i experience my life fully and completely in love with the person i am.

if you are ready to do the work to transform your life and how you experience it, i'm here to help. 
just click the link on my bio to book a free discovery call.

text:
#mauravation:
as a survivor of gang rape, i never knew that my biggest challenge as a teenager would end up helping others deal with their childhood secrets. learning to have courage gave me a voice that i now use to inspire others to share their stories. so if you or someone you know has been abused violated or shamed please remind them they are not alone. encourage them, embrace them and equip them with the truth of who and more importantly who‚Äôs they are. don‚Äôt allow them to go at it alone...you are not alone.
you are strong, resilient, loved and empowered, which ensures others don‚Äôt have to fight alone.

to learn more purchase my autobiography ‚Äúbeyond blessed‚Äù on my website (link in bio) or get a copy of our film ‚Äústem the movement‚Äù available on dvd.

project tofa is heading to kyabirwa, a small village near jinja, uganda!

name: NIKI HARRIS | Life Coach
tweet_full: #rkelly#abuse#sexualabuse#mentalabuse#physicalabuse#domesticabuse#emotionalabuse#noexcuses#metoo#womenempoweringwomen#lifecoachforwomen

text:
great morning, beautiful ones. 
in lieu of #surviving..., along with the climate of the world, i am reminding survivors of abuse of any kind, it is not your fault. abuse is about power and control. 
the cycle of abuse looks like this- 
honeymoon stage- abuser is a sweet manipulator. you are swept off your feet 
egg shells - abuser gets upset at little things and you don‚Äôt even know why or what you did, so you try not to piss them off 
explosion - abuser goes off (verbally, emotionally, physically, sexually) 
with love, i nudge you to employ the following ideas: -please take care of your emotional well being, if you felt/feel triggered in any way. 
1. turn off the show  or shows about abuse. 
2. do not engage in combative and ignorant people in person or online. 
3.find safe spaces in person or online that support you and other survivors/friends or family of survivors. -seek support from loving, proactive, authentic people in your life and professional help. (a therapist/ an organization/police/spiritual support) -honor your own process. 
to abusers-seek professional help. you hurt people because you‚Äôve been hurt in some way, shape or form in your life‚Äôs journey. it‚Äôs healing time. we can no longer support destructive behavior in our community. 
note- as a survior and now transformer of sexual assault and domestic violence, i share this with love and healing light. 
i love you. 
i support you. 
felicia webster

#inspirationalquotes #motivationalquotes 
#cycleofabuse 
#survivor #abuse #metoo #domesticviolence #domesticviolenceawareness

text:
hey guys, here's the list of my 10 favourite films from before 2018 and 2017 that i first watched last year:

#10 west side story (directed by jerome robbins and robert wise, 1961) ‚Äì i finally watched this musical classic this year, and let me tell you, this is such a technical feat! everything about this film is done to perfection, from the direction to the cinematography and the editing. if the incredible choreography of this musical won‚Äôt bewitch you, the vivid colours will. and not only that, this film is able to tell a very important story that deals with segregation and racism, which is very impressive considering the time when it was produced. this is definitely a classic that should be watched by any true lover of cinema.

#9 yol (directed by serif g√∂ren and yilmaz g√ºney, 1982) ‚Äì let me tell you, this film floored me to the ground. this film was mostly forgotten since it premiered to rave reviews in cannes and won the palm d‚Äôor, and that is one of the greatest injustices of this world because this is one of the greatest masterpieces ever made and a testament of the power of cinema. this is a poetic film about five prisoners that are given a week‚Äôs leave from prison and the way they see society outside of prison. it‚Äôs a stark and real portrait of turkey that is filled with such emotion that it‚Äôs impossible not to be moved by it. what is so impressive about this film is how yilmaz g√ºney directed it from prison, being able to only see the dailies, and was able to make such a great film with such a strong and important message, which only proves how, when you have something to say, you‚Äôll do everything in your power to say it despite all odds. (list continues in comments)

text:
#metoo ! majanga yaendelea kumuandama r.kelly baada ya kituo cha tv cha lifetime kuanza kurusha docuseries kuhusu unyanyasaji wa kingono kwa wanawake na wasichana wadogo uliofanywa na r.kelly.
.
.
series hiyo yenye sehemu sita kituo hicho kinaonesha kufanya mahojiano na ndugu wa r.kelly, familia yake, marafiki na wafanyakazi wenzie lakini hasa wanawake mbalimbali na mabinti wadogo waliojitokeza kuvunja ukimya wa kunyanyaswa kingono na star huyo ambaye anadaiwa kutumia nguvu na ushawishi wake vibaya kufanya unyanyasaji wa kingono kwa matamanio yake binafsi bila kujali kuathiri wengine
.
ukiacha hao wengine walionekana kwenye documentary hiyo ni chance the rapper ambaye amekiri kujutia kufanya kazi na r.kelly kwa unyanyasaji aliowafanyia wanawake, john legend nae katika docuseries hiyo anaonekana kumfumua r.kelly kwa kusema amesababisha maumivu makubwa kwa watu wengi, john legend ambaye ni baba wa watoto wawili amekuwa mstari wa mbele kwa muda sasa kusapoti movement ya #metoo ili kuwapa sapoti wanawake wanaonyanyaswa kingono kwa nguvu hasa maeneo ya kazi .
.
.
wengine waliotoa ushirikiano kwenye documentary hiyo ni pamoja na wendy williams, tarana mwanzilishi wa #metoomovement na wengineo .
hata hivyo mwanasheria wa r.kelly amechimba biti kuwa watashitaki kwa madai mteja wake kuchafuliwa

text:
learned about a pioneer of not only medicine but civil rights while at @stanford university school of medicine the other day and thought this would be extremely relevant especially with the climate we are living in.

dr. frances k. conley in 1975 she became the first female faculty member at stanford in any surgical department, in 1977, she became the fifth woman to become a board certified neurosurgeon in the united states, in 1982 the first woman to be granted a tenured professorship in neurosurgery at a u.s. medical school and in 1986, the first to have a full professorship.

in june 1991, she publicly resigned from @stanford university in protest over the work environment that included sexist attitudes and outright sexual harassment. when conley resigned from stanford university, her book walking out on the boys was released and provided a very in depth and firsthand look at the sexism that really went on at the university

#metoo #wetoo #pioneer #medicine
